How we engage
Embedded development team
Short or long-term engagements where Innovise is the client's engineering department. Can scale up or down depending on the initiative. The most common starting point.

From MVP to production
For companies that built fast -- with AI tools, contractors, or founders writing code -- and now have a fragile codebase that won't scale or can't be handed off. Innovise audits what exists, stabilizes it for production use, and gets it to a state that can be maintained or extended. The first question is always what can be saved, not whether to rewrite. Typical engagement: 4 to 8 weeks.

Internal team development
Helping companies build their own engineering teams from the ground up or transition from an offshore model. Covers hiring support, interim coverage while the hiring runs, and a structured handoff plan. Innovise does not build dependency -- the goal is a team that can operate independently.

Technical retainer
A senior engineer monitoring systems and available for strategic questions on an ongoing basis. Designed for businesses that need steady technical oversight between initiatives.

Technology and security audit
A structured, one-time assessment of tech stack, security posture, and cloud spend. Produces honest findings and a prioritized roadmap. Not a pitch for the next engagement. Less common as a starting point -- most clients come through project work -- but useful for companies needing a second opinion or pre-acquisition technical due diligence.

Voice and tone guidelines
All Innovise content should reflect the following principles:
Directness
Lead with outcomes and concrete specifics. Avoid hedging, filler, and corporate warmth.
Specificity over adjectives
Describe quality through specifics (senior engineers, direct access, no handoffs) rather than through adjectives (boutique, world-class, best-in-class).
No jargon
Avoid: "end-to-end solutions," "best-in-class," "leverage," "synergy," "modern methodologies," "industry best practices."
Earned trust
Innovise earns trust through honesty about how it works, not through claims about being the best.
Formatting
Sentence case for all headings. No unnecessary capitalization.

Copy framing decisions (hard-won through iteration)
These are specific decisions made after testing copy against the brand and reviewing how buyers actually read it. Follow them unless there's a clear reason to revisit.

Lead with how the work is done, not what it saves.
The original homepage H1 read "Your engineering team, without the overhead of building one." This frames Innovise on cost avoidance, which attracts buyers who evaluate on price. Buyers who arrive at "someone who actually does the work themselves" evaluate on accountability and fit. Preferred framing: describe the model directly ("Senior engineers who do the work themselves") rather than the thing it replaces ("without the overhead").

Don't overclaim on the team model.
Copy that says "senior talent, assembled for your work" and "no hand-me-down capacity" sits in direct contradiction to the reality that blended teams (including mid-level and junior developers) are sometimes used. The accurate description: Loren leads every engagement; when more capacity is needed, supporting engineers are brought in; clients always know who's on the project and at what level. Claims about team composition must match what actually gets delivered.

Describe the first call honestly.
Innovise's differentiation extends to the sales process, not just the delivery. Copy that describes how the first call works ("about 30 minutes, goes both directions, no pitch until we've talked, we'll say if we're not the right fit") is more credible and more aligned with the brand than generic "let's talk" language. Buyers who've been burned by pushy agencies respond to specificity about process.

Geographic references are consistent: Bellevue, WA.
"Bellevue, WA" is the standard form for all location references. "Seattle" is acceptable as a metro-area reference in contextual copy (e.g., CTA eyebrow, regional references) but should not appear as the primary location. "Seattle, Washington" is incorrect and was the source of a geographic inconsistency caught in review. The hero eyebrow ("Bellevue, WA · serving clients nationwide") is the canonical form for above-the-fold location signal.

The hero eyebrow carries local SEO and buyer-orientation signal.
The homepage hero eyebrow (the small all-caps line above the H1) is one of the first things a buyer sees. Generic labels like "Engineering Partner" waste that position. Using it for location + geographic scope ("Bellevue, WA · serving clients nationwide") gives local SEO signal above the fold and immediately orients the buyer. Prefer specific over label-like.

Service card eyebrows can carry niche recognition.
When a service card targets a buyer who may not immediately recognize themselves in the card title alone, an eyebrow helps. The MVP-to-production card uses "AI-generated code · vibe-coded MVPs" because the buyer searching for help with a fragile Cursor or Bolt codebase may not self-identify as needing "From MVP to production." Eyebrows are optional — use them when a service has a specific buyer profile that benefits from naming.

