Notes:
- The fractional CTO doesn't scale really well. It's a service Innovise offers, but it shouldn't be the top-promoted unit.
- Blended teams (senior + mid-level + junior developers) are available to help clients manage costs and support the software industry.
- "From MVP to production" is a new, growing service niche. The target: founders or PMs who built with AI tools (Cursor, Bolt, Replit) or fast contractors, now have fragile code. Positioning: honest assessment first, no automatic rewrites.
- "Internal team development" is a real, distinct service -- not just a footnote of embedded teams. The ed-tech client story (offshore to 25 onshore FTEs) is the primary proof point. The SRE continuity story is a secondary proof point.
- Technology audits happen but are rarely an entry point. Most clients come through direct project work. The audit page still has SEO value and serves clients needing a second opinion or pre-acquisition due diligence.

SEO copy decisions:
- MVP-to-production page: name Cursor, Bolt, and Replit in the first paragraph of "Who this is for" (not just in FAQ). These are high-intent search terms for the target buyer. They also belong in the meta description.
- Internal team development page: "offshore to onshore" is a direct search phrase and belongs in the page title, meta description, and hero eyebrow or subhead. "Engineering team development" alone does not capture that intent.
- The homepage hero eyebrow ("Bellevue, WA · serving clients nationwide") provides above-the-fold local SEO signal. Do not replace it with a generic label.
- Page titles should lead with the problem or service niche, not the company name. Company name goes last (e.g., "Fix Your MVP Codebase — From AI Tools to Production-Ready | Innovise", not "Innovise | MVP Services").
- Meta descriptions should name specific buyer situations and tools where relevant. Generic descriptions ("we help businesses with software") produce low CTR.


Various case studies and examples of what Innovise has offered

Story 1 -- Sports technology / cloud audit
Sports technology company needed to reduce their Azure spend. Innovise audited their technology and how it was hosted in Azure. Updated services from dedicated VMs to Docker containers. Monthly Azure spend dropped 80%.

Story 2 -- Real estate startup / SaaS build
A recently-funded real estate startup needed to build a SaaS web application. Innovise was contracted to build it. 3 developers worked together with the CEO as product owner, running daily standups using agile methodology. As the project approached MVP, the team scaled back to a single developer to match the budget. The MVP shipped. The client paid for exactly the capacity they needed.

Story 3 -- Ed-tech / offshore to onshore transition
An ed-tech client had most of their software built offshore by several different teams. Thin context, long feedback loop, accumulating technical debt. The client decided to transition to an onshore team. Loren helped plan and structure the hiring process while Innovise developers stepped in on a contract-to-hire basis. End result: the client built up to a 25-person onshore staff, a mix of FTEs and contractors.

Story 4 -- Mobile app vs. web refactor (honest pushback)
A client wanted a native mobile app. Innovise walked through the actual cost and complexity of building and maintaining two codebases. With targeted refactoring, the web application served the mobile audience without a second product. The client saved months of development time and ongoing maintenance overhead.

Story 5 -- Backend rewrite vs. targeted refactoring (honest pushback)
A client wanted their backend API rebuilt from scratch because "it was built by someone else." Innovise reviewed the code and found the core architecture was sound -- surface-level inconsistencies, some cleanup needed. A targeted refactor fixed what mattered. The client kept a working system instead of a multi-month rebuild.

Story 6 -- SPA to React Router 7 instead of Next.js migration (honest pushback)
A client needed to improve SEO and SSR for their React application. The team proposed a full Next.js migration. Innovise found that React Router 7 -- a much lighter lift using the same framework -- covered everything needed. No one learned a new framework, the migration took a fraction of the time, and the SEO improvements came out the same.

Story 7 -- Search feature: Algolia pipeline instead of backend rewrite (honest audit)
A client's in-house team insisted adding search required a full backend rewrite and database migrations. Innovise was contracted to assess. The actual solution: a lightweight write pipeline that synced a subset of fields to an Algolia index on each record update. No migrations, no schema changes. The search feature shipped in a fraction of the time and budget estimated.

Story 8 -- SRE continuity (coverage gap)
A client's full-time SRE engineer resigned. Replacing them through standard hiring was going to take months. An Innovise engineer already embedded in the team stepped into the role immediately. No gap in operations, no lost context. The hiring ran in parallel and the new hire came into a stable system.

Story 9 -- Offshore team QA and management
A client had offshore developers building a mobile app but needed a senior developer they could trust to audit and manage the project. The Innovise developer provided full-time support, ensuring quality while working alongside the offshore team.

Story 10 -- Mobile app team assembly
A client needed to build a mobile app to accompany their web app. Unable to find a cohesive team, they approached Innovise. Innovise assembled a team of developers and a designer who worked embedded in the org alongside the client's PMO. The team built the app and educated the client on mobile-specific processes: App Store releases, deep links, and related technologies.
